DESCRIPTION
etude is an AI-agent-first CLI primitive, but an agent starting a new session (or recovering after a context compaction/clear) has no fast, authoritative way to learn what etude is and how to use it — today it must read scattered docs/BRIEF/source and may hallucinate not-yet-implemented commands. Add an 'etude prime' subcommand (mirroring 'bd prime') that prints a single, structured, READ-ONLY primer to stdout so an AI agent can bootstrap its understanding in one command.

The primer should cover: (1) what etude is and its purpose (empirically test AI coding-agent skills by replaying past work); (2) core concepts (workflow, stage, artifact, run, replay, eval, cohort, bench) per BRIEF.md section 3; (3) the storage model (custom refs/etude/* namespace, content-addressed artifacts under artifacts/sha256/*, per-run manifest.json); (4) a command reference that CLEARLY marks IMPLEMENTED (init, capture, run list/show, sync) vs PLANNED / not-yet-built (replay, eval, bench, import) so the agent does not invoke missing commands; (5) the typical capture workflow and the .etude/workflow.yaml config.

Must run anywhere: no git repo required, no network, no side effects (pure stdout, exit 0). Keep it concise but complete — optimized for an agent's context budget.

DESIGN
## Plan

**Approach:** Add a top-level `etude prime` cobra command that prints a static, structured READ-ONLY primer to stdout and exits 0 anywhere (no refstore, no git, no network, no writes). Mirror the bd prime shape. The primer body is built in Go (not a docs file) so it is always available offline: a static template for purpose/concepts/storage/workflow sections plus a DYNAMICALLY-DERIVED 'available commands' list. To kill implemented-vs-planned drift, the available list is generated at runtime by walking cmd.Root().Commands() and emitting each non-hidden subcommand's Use+Short (recursing one level so run list/show and retro list/show/capture/generate appear). PLANNED-but-unregistered commands (standalone `eval`, `import`) live in a separate explicit 'Planned / not yet built' section. NOTE: the bead's stale lists are wrong — derive from the live tree (bench/capture/capture-gate/capture-run/gc/init/reindex/replay/retro/run/sync are all SHIPPED).

**Files:**
- internal/cli/prime.go - new. newPrimeCommand(out, errOut). cobra.Command{Use: "prime", Short, Args: cobra.NoArgs, SilenceUsage/Errors}. RunE walks cmd.Root().Commands(), skips hidden + the auto 'help'/'completion' commands, formats each via a renderPrimer(root) helper that splices the derived command list into the static template, writes to cmd.OutOrStdout(). The registered `prime` command IS included in the derived available-commands list (it is a real command an agent can run); do NOT special-case-exclude prime from its own primer. No refstore.New, no git calls.
- internal/cli/prime_test.go - new. Drift-proofing + content + side-effect-free tests (below).
- internal/cli/root.go - add cmd.AddCommand(newPrimeCommand(out, errOut)) in alpha order (after newInitCommand / before newReindexCommand).

**Primer sections (concise, agent-context-budget):**
1. WHAT/PURPOSE: etude empirically tests AI coding-agent skills by capturing stage artifacts as git-native run records and replaying past work.
2. CORE CONCEPTS (per BRIEF s3): workflow, stage (inputs->output), artifact (content-addressed immutable blob), run (one workflow pass w/ manifest), replay, eval (rubric/pairwise/assertion — library, no CLI), cohort, bench (headline: replay+eval a stage across a cohort).
3. STORAGE MODEL: refs/etude/* namespace (runs/<id>, evals/<id>), content-addressed artifacts under artifacts/sha256/<aa>/<hash>, per-run manifest.json (manifest_version 2, stages w/ producer harness/model/skill + git_sha).
4. COMMANDS: 'Available' (derived from cobra tree, with Short — includes prime itself) + 'Planned / not yet built' = standalone eval CLI (eval is a library used by bench), import (xenota/GitHub, Phase 1).
5. WORKFLOW: typical capture flow + .etude/workflow.yaml (name + ordered stages w/ produces/inputs/skill/eval) created by 'etude init'.

**Tests (prime_test.go):**
- TestPrimeRunsAnywhere: ExecuteWithWriters(prime) in a NON-git temp dir (t.Chdir to t.TempDir) -> err==nil, stderr=='', non-empty stdout. Confirms no repo/git/side-effect dependency.
- TestPrimeDriftGuard (the key test): build root via NewRootCommand, walk EVERY registered non-hidden subcommand name (+ one level of subcommands), assert each appears in prime output. The registered `prime` command is NOT excluded from this assertion — prime appears in its own primer and is covered by the guard like any other command. (If for some reason the primer would naturally omit a command, the test must account for that explicitly; default is: prime is present + covered.) Adding a future command without it surfacing in the primer FAILS this test. Also assert the planned-list names (eval, import) are NOT registered commands (no overlap / mislabel).
- TestPrimeContent: stdout contains the section anchors + key terms (refs/etude/, artifacts/sha256, manifest.json, workflow.yaml, bench, replay) and the 'Planned' markers for eval/import.
- TestPrimeNoArgs: `prime foo` -> error (cobra.NoArgs).

**Docs:**
- The etude-712 drift guard DOES enumerate the cobra command tree, so adding the new `prime` command WILL require a generated CLI reference page. The Docs phase MUST run `make docs` to (a) generate a new docs/cli/etude_prime.md page and (b) refresh docs/cli/etude.md with the new subcommand entry; the new page must be committed. `make docs-check` and `TestDriftGuard` MUST be green before advancing. (No additional hand-written prose docs are required by the acceptance criteria — the primer ships in-binary.)

**Risks:** Low. Read-only, isolated. Only nuance: the drift test must account for cobra's auto-injected 'help'/'completion' commands and any hidden flags/commands so the derive-and-assert logic stays stable; mitigated by filtering hidden + the help/completion names.

